This code returns the order of courses to take (topological ordering) given prerequisite constraints using Kahn's algorithm (BFS-based topological sort). 
It builds a directed graph where an edge pre[1] → pre[0] means the prerequisite must be taken before the course, and computes the indegree (number of prerequisites) for each course.
All courses with zero indegree are added to a queue, then repeatedly a course is removed from the queue, appended to the result order,
and its outgoing edges are "removed" by decrementing the indegree of neighboring courses — if any neighbor's indegree becomes zero, it is added to the queue.
If the number of courses in the final order equals numCourses, the order array is returned; otherwise (cycle detected), an empty array is returned.

Time Complexity: O(V + E) — where V = numCourses and E = number of prerequisites; each vertex and edge is processed once.
Space Complexity: O(V + E) — for the adjacency list, indegree array, queue, and order array.


class Solution {
    public int[] findOrder(int numCourses, int[][] prerequisites) {
        List<Integer>[] graph = new ArrayList[numCourses];
        for(int i = 0; i<numCourses; i++){
            graph[i] = new ArrayList<>();
        }
        int[] indegree = new int[numCourses];
        for(int[] pre: prerequisites){
            graph[pre[1]].add(pre[0]);
            indegree[pre[0]]++;
        }
        Queue<Integer> q = new LinkedList<>();
        for(int i = 0; i<numCourses; i++){
            if(indegree[i] == 0){
                q.offer(i);
            }
        }
        int[] order = new int[numCourses];
        int idx = 0;
        while(!q.isEmpty()) {
            int curr = q.poll();
            order[idx++] = curr;
            for(int nbr : graph[curr]){
                indegree[nbr]--;
                if(indegree[nbr] == 0){
                    q.offer(nbr);
                }
            }
        }
        return idx == numCourses ? order : new int[0];
    }
}
